<br>
Level II should have given a 10% bonus and affected all spells ABOVE level 20.<br>
<br>
Level III should have given a 15% bonus and affected all spells ABOVE level 44.<br>
<br>
This would allow those mid range casters in the 55 to 60 range that don't belong to large raiding guilds to have some focus effects. As it stands now it only affects those casters in large raiding guilds. This does nothing to balance casters, as good melee loot is still generally available. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
I think the focus item system you're describing is FAR more sensible than the one currently in place. More importantly, it fits better with VI's stated intention: <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> adding focus effects on existing items as part of caster balance</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
This is another example of exactly what is wrong with VI's interpretation of caster balance. If a caster class is generally imbalanced at a certain level, it is absurd to think that you're going to balance that entire class by adding abilities/spells/equipment that are only available to a certain portion of those playing the class.<br>
<br>
For many, this would be like VI discovering that all 9th level spells had been deleted from druid vendors. So in the next patch, they put all the 9th level druid spells back in the game-- on an iksar vendor in the middle of Cabilis, requiring ally faction to buy it. Yes, a &quot;solution&quot; to the problem exists, but those who need it most can't get to it. <br>
<br>
A class itself being imbalanced is not going to be fixed by new or retuned items **unless** those items are **reasonably** available to all the members of that class. <br>
<br>
Let's say a manufacturer defect was found to exist on a certain make/model of Goodyear automobile tire, causing the tire to EXPLODE at a certain temperature. Let's say Goodyear was charged with correcting this by replacing a faulty valve stem. So, the folks at Goodyear proceed with setting up a repair facility-- on the top of Mount Everest. They smugly advertise that all those who need the repair must bring their cars to the designated repair facility.<br>
<br>
Have they fufilled their responsibility of addressing the problem? Well, technically the answer is yes.<br>
<br>
However, the issue is not &quot;can&quot; someone get their automobile to the top of Mount Everest. The issue is &quot;how reasonable&quot; is it to expect them to.  No doubt, there are certainly folks with access to equipment for air-lifting a car to the top of a mountain! But does that really address the problem for &quot;all&quot; owners of those faulty Goodyear tires?<br>
<br>
And no, one shouldn't have to &quot;downgrade&quot; their equipment to have focus effects. But VI made a HUGE mistake in basing focus additions too much on the assumption of twinking. They made a HUGE mistake by assuming that no one over 44th level would still be using many *decent* mid-level items. Well, decent until you discover that VI's interpretation of decent for level 45 means NToV or better. <br>
<br>
When I see that:<br>
- one of my items has a focus III effect that druids can't even use, and<br>
- one of my items has a focus III effect that is insanely useless 99.9% of the time, and<br>
- two of my items have focus II effects which are useless for any of the spells I rely on, and<br>
- if I want any focus III items that are useful to 44+ druid spells I can expect to pay thousands of plat for an item and then probably put it in a slot where I had an item with more appropriate stats for my class,<br>
<br>
 ...I can honestly say that I don't feel very much a part of this round of caster balance.<br>
<br>
